For anyone contemplating building, an essential :: In 1953, Japanese architect Junzo Yoshimura designed a now-classic Japanese house and garden that he called Shofuso. It was built in Nagoya, Japan, and shipped to New York in 1954, where it was exhibited at the Museum of Modern Art and then relocated to Philadelphia’s Fairmount Park. The curators of MoMA’s House in the Garden exhibition highlighted its synthesis of historic Japanese architecture with modern architecture: the clarity of the house’s post and beam structure, its flexibility of use and the close relationship of indoor and outdoor spaces.

Only 4 copies left, I suggest getting your hands on one :: “The space surrounding my work is crucial to it,” Donald Judd wrote in 1977: “as much thought has gone into the installation as into a piece itself.” Featured spreads are from the Judd Foundation’s gorgeous, 432-page new edition of Donald Judd Spaces, documenting the artist’s iconic, and ultimately highly influential, living and working spaces in New York and around Marfa, Texas. Featuring exquisite new photographs, drawing details and archival materials, and packaged in a special glassine wrap, this is a book that is virtually impossible to put down, both visually and physically. “Both three-dimensional art—painting is a somewhat ambiguous situation—and architecture make space,” he also wrote in 1977. “You could say they define space, but that assumes that space existed prior to the definition, which is debatable. By making lines or points or planes in space, you actually make the space. The thing that a person likes most about three-dimensional art or architecture is the created space. That’s the main given aspect of it—basically, it’s that and the color.”

“Figure Study”, by Peter Cusack, watercolor on paper with maple frame :: Peter Cusack’s practice is rooted in his drawings of lived experiences, cultural observations, and early 19th Century French art. In the face of a society that can feel chaotic, 19th Century art offers him a solace: a reverence for humanity and for how we fit into nature. It is this dichotomy, between chaos and order, that informs Cusack’s paintings. Many of the figures Cusack depicts are representations of loved ones passed. Their presence in his paintings are both palpable and abstract, much like memories. Through painting, Cusack is at once externalizing his own memory, while simultaneously examining our collective history and relationship to the human form through art.

Today on the journal, a reflection on our connection to the community and land in the Hudson Valley, by @millionwalker :: video by @soulsoilsol @emmalmccann edited by @terrronce :: “If Block Island is the inhale of our business, the Hudson Valley is the exhale. It’s where our Germantown gallery and jewelry studio are, open year round. The Hudson Valley side of our business is there to keep us anchored, to help us prepare and see through our busy months, and to connect us with the wealth of creatives that have also made their home here.
A big part of what helps us ground our team in the Hudson Valley is the land - the trails down the street, the Catskill mountains in the distance, the ponds for our dogs to cool off in in the summer. The environment which affects us whether we actively engage with it or not - even driving to work down our twisty country roads — sets us up to handle our tools a little more gently, with more breeze between our actions.“

Transitioning back to the land :: we donated a portion of sales from our High Summer Collection to the @clctrust this past week. Since their founding in 1986, CLC has been working to conserve Columbia County’s important landscapes and connect people to nature. CLC has secured over 12,000 acres of land and has collaborated with 250 easement landowners owning 29,984 acres of conserved land to ensure they are protected in perpetuity. The land they steward has provided our team with countless mid-day walks, team strolls, runs to clear our busy minds, and much-needed nature time for our dogs. The accessibility we have to green space around us has simply led to a healthier team, a more balanced work-life rhythm, and more inspired jewelry collections. “The hand-painted patterning that fully envelops these objects draws from the natural world and our own built world. Grids, growths, and forms break and attach to each other, generating a skin that ushers the object into being. They are individuals, like a living thing; each piece is a unique force, yet strives to be a universally beautiful object that carries with it a long history of love and care. When we live with objects, they become extensions and reflections of ourselves.” @_natch_ on his process :: Like a Living Thing — a show featuring work from @_natch_ and @chrismottalini opens this Friday, September 22nd 5-7pm in Germantown :: 📷 @emmalmccann
Fall collection — inspired by Anaïs Nin, sensuality, and small, private worlds of texture — on view Friday in Germantown, online next week

Chris Mottalini is a Hudson Valley-based artist known for his portrait-like approach to architectural photography. Chris’ work interacts with the chosen spaces he photographs, intentionally framing each shot to convey the specific light, texture, and ethereal quality of a place. “Like a Living Thing” presents Chris’ exploration of Anaïs Nin’s LA refuge in Silverlake. Chris’ work allows access to Nin’s most personal space – filled with rich wood grain corners, painted portraits of the exuberant author, soaked in golden light, and saturated with deep purple, mauve, and turquoise hues. The combination of details in Chris’ photographs evokes an authentic celebration of Nin’s unique character and the nourishment she gained from being in Silverlake. She wrote, “Had I not created my whole world, I would certainly have died in other people’s.”

Last week we hosted a dinner at @king.newyork to celebrate the launch of our new sterling silver men’s line, Paulsen. The most gracious cheerleader, @kateberryberry brought the vision to life — a simple table with piles of Block Island stones holding candles, branches of red oaks reminiscent of fall in the Hudson Valley, and a brilliantly comforting yet bright meal from the genius’ at King. The guests varied from renown artists, writers, curators, stylists, and designers — dear friends, new friends, and friends to one another. It was a complete joy 💫 moments captured by @sarahirenemurphy of @__milesandmiles__

Leading up to the dinner at @king.newyork our studio crafted pieces fit for each guest — a prompt in the tradition of our  wire jewelry north stars Calder and Kazuko Oshima who both famously made pieces inspired by friends and patrons of the arts. Thank you to all who attended, particularly for this burst of inspiration. Plus, the revival of brooches (ahem thank you @ryanpatrickkelley)! Photos by @sarahirenemurphy of @__milesandmiles__
